  <datafield tag="245" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Feasibility study of a flux-gate magnetic field sensor suitable for ITER neutral beam injectors</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="260" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="c">2017-03-19</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="520" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">• Magnetic sensors which are robust, radiation hard, drift-immune and remote-handling compatible are required for measuring the magnetic field inside the ITER Heating Neutral beam injectors (HNBs). • Each HNB is surrounded by a Passive Magnetic Shield (PMS) and by feedback-controlled Active Correction and Compensation Coils (ACCC), so as to guarantee that the stray magnetic field produced by the Poloidal Field Coils of the ITER tokamak is within acceptable limits. • To this purpose, flux-gate magnetic sensors are a good candidate, even though commercial sensors of this kind have typically a limited measured range. • The applicability of flux-gate sensors to the ITER HNB has been studied by developing a numerical model and by building and testing a flux-gate sensor prototype. • Experiments carried out so far have demonstrated that the measurement range can achieve the required range with acceptable accuracy and frequency bandwidth.</subfield>
